<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="685" pageId="3" pageNumber="684" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1211,1515,1700]" box="[677,777,1515,1541]" pageId="3" pageNumber="684">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1211,1515,1700]" lastBlockId="4.[111,648,216,781]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="685" pageId="3" pageNumber="684">
As explained in the diagnosis below, within the Malagasy and African/Middle East species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobson" authorityYear="1871" box="[750,854,1611,1636]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="684" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[750,854,1611,1636]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="684">Triaenops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are two distinct 
<typeStatus box="[1120,1178,1610,1637]" pageId="3" pageNumber="684">types</typeStatus>
of noseleafs that clearly distinguish two different groups in this genus (
<bibRefCitation author="HILL J. E." box="[918,1033,1673,1700]" pageId="3" pageNumber="684" pagination="165 - 177" refId="ref8586" refString="HILL J. E. 1982. - A review of the leaf-nosed bats Rhinonycteris, Cloeotis and Triaenops (Chiroptera: Hipposideridae). Bonner Zoologisches Beitrage 33: 165 - 177." type="journal article" year="1982">Hill 1982</bibRefCitation>
). In this respect the material from the western 
<collectingCountry box="[425,530,216,243]" name="Seychelles" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
is referable to the 
<emphasis box="[183,373,247,273]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. Grandidier" authorityYear="1912" box="[183,278,247,273]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="auritus">T. auritus</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Trouessart" authorityYear="1906" box="[289,373,247,273]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="furculus">furculus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
group, rather than to the 
<emphasis box="[113,271,279,305]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1881" box="[113,188,279,305]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rufus">T. rufus</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobson" authorityYear="1871" box="[198,271,279,305]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="persicus">persicus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
group. Thus, in making our detailed evaluations we have used specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Trouessart" authorityYear="1906" box="[501,604,311,337]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="furculus">
<emphasis box="[501,604,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">T. furculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. Grandidier" authorityYear="1912" box="[113,211,343,368]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="auritus">
<emphasis box="[113,211,343,368]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">T. auritus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from near their 
<typeStatus box="[382,428,343,370]" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">type</typeStatus>
localities, which are, respectively, extreme southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[489,616,374,401]" name="Madagascar" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
in the general vicinity of Sarodrano and the Ankarana region near 
<collectingRegion box="[239,369,438,465]" country="Madagascar" name="Antsiranana" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Antsiranana</collectingRegion>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="RANIVO J. &amp; GOODMAN S. M." pageId="4" pageNumber="685" pagination="963 - 985" refId="ref8848" refString="RANIVO J. &amp; GOODMAN S. M. 2006. - Revision taxinomique des Triaenops malgaches (Mammalia, Chiroptera, Hipposideridae). Zoosystema 28 (4): 963 - 985." type="journal article" year="2006">Ranivo &amp; Goodman 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[183,244,469,496]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="2.[113,124,1301,1318]" captionTargetBox="[279,1042,220,1261]" captionTargetId="graphics-19@2.[239,1084,162,1315]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIG. 1. — Map of the islands of the western Seychelles Archipelago (Aldabra, Cosmoledo, and Assumption), Madagascar, and the east African coast showing the distribution of the different Triaenops species occurring across the western Indian Ocean.○, T. auritus G. Grandidier, 1912; △, T. furculus Trouessart, 1906; + +, T. rufus A. Milne-Edwards, 1881; □, T. pauliani n. sp. Note that Aldabra is to the northwest of the northern tip of Madagascar and these two zones form an almost equidistant triangle with the Comoro Islands." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5755726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5755726/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[111,648,216,781]" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">
On the basis of our comparisons of the western 
<collectingCountry box="[113,222,533,560]" name="Seychelles" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobson" authorityYear="1871" box="[361,462,533,558]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[361,462,533,558]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Triaenops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to specimens of this genus from 
<collectingCountry box="[291,419,564,591]" name="Madagascar" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, as well as Africa and the Middle East, animals from the former locality possess unique morphological characters and certain measurements fall outside of the range of any previously named species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobson" authorityYear="1871" box="[467,566,692,717]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinonycteridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="685" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[467,566,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Triaenops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Given these differences, we consider the western 
<collectingCountry box="[542,646,723,750]" name="Seychelles" pageId="4" pageNumber="685">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
material to be new to science.
</paragraph>
